                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d582">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1770</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-18T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 18, 1915, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your 2226, May 17. Inasmuch as there will be time if necessary to give advice to
                    Americans resident in Germany after receipt of <pb facs="0657" n="399"
                        xml:id="pg_399"/> German Government’s reply, Department does not desire to
                    take initiative now. You may however, as a precaution, advise the consuls
                    confidentially to keep closely in touch with the Americans in their respective
                    districts so that communication may be the more prompt if it is found necessary
                    to give any instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
